text:
Lightly the breeze laughs in her sunlit keep;  
Murmurs the bee in a dull ear;  
Sing the sweet birds in their heedless measure, --  
Ah, what wisdom has died away here!

source_text:
Light laughs the breeze in her castle of sunshine;
Babbles the bee in a stolid ear;
Pipe the sweet birds in ignorant cadence, --
Ah, what sagacity perished here!

text:
Let me drink from the spirit of that sweet sound,  
More, oh more—I am still athirst;  
It uncoils the serpent care has wound  
Around my heart to hold it fast;  
The melting note, through every vein,  
Moves into my heart and brain.

source_text:
Let me drink of the spirit of that sweet sound,
More, oh more,—I am thirsting yet;
It loosens the serpent which care has bound
Upon my heart to stifle it;
The dissolving strain, through every vein,
Passes into my heart and brain.

text:
MEPHISTOPHELES:
What crowding, crashing, surging, shuddering;
What whispering, babbling, hissing, scurrying;
What flickering, spitting, reeking, blazing,
As though both Heaven and Earth were turning over.
There is a true witch-fire in this place;
Hold fast to me, or we will be torn apart:—
Where are you?

source_text:
MEPHISTOPHELES:
What thronging, dashing, raging, rustling;
What whispering, babbling, hissing, bustling;
What glimmering, spurting, stinking, burning,
As Heaven and Earth were overturning.
There is a true witch element about us;
Take hold on me, or we shall be divided:—
Where are you?

Here Stuarts once in glory reigned,
And laws for Scotland’s weal ordained;
But now unroof’d their palace stands,
Their sceptre’s sway’d by other hands;
Fallen indeed, and to the earth
Whence groveling reptiles take their birth.
The injured Stuart line is gone,
A race outlandish fills their throne;
An idiot race, to honour lost;
Who know them best despise them most.

text:
O newest-born, and fairest shape afar  
Among Olympus’ dim and dying throng!  
More fair than Phoebe’s sapphire-set bright star,  
Or Vesper, heaven’s enamored glow-worm long;  
More fair than these, though thou hast no holy place,  
No altar heaped with blooms;  
Nor maiden-choir to breathe a sweet, low grace  
Through the midnight’s dusky rooms;  
No voice, no lute, no pipe, no fragrant smoke  
From a swinging censer flowing;  
No shrine, no grove, no oracle, no stroke  
Of pale-lipped prophet’s knowing.

source_text:
O latest born and loveliest vision far
Of all Olympus' faded hierarchy!
Fairer than Phoebe's sapphire-region'd star,
Or Vesper, amorous glow-worm of the sky;
Fairer than these, though temple thou hast none,
Nor altar heap'd with flowers;
Nor virgin-choir to make delicious moan
Upon the midnight hours;
No voice, no lute, no pipe, no incense sweet
From chain-swung censer teeming;
No shrine, no grove, no oracle, no heat
Of pale-mouth'd prophet dreaming.

text:
The sun has gone; the swallows rest in sleep;  
The bats move swiftly through the fading air;  
From dampened corners, slow soft toads emerge and creep,  
And evening’s breath, drifting everywhere,  
Above the trembling face of the stream,  
Stirs not one ripple from its summer dream.

source_text:
The sun is set; the swallows are asleep;
The bats are flitting fast in the gray air;
The slow soft toads out of damp corners creep,
And evening’s breath, wandering here and there
Over the quivering surface of the stream,
Wakes not one ripple from its summer dream.

text:
Little boy,  
Bright with delight;  
Little girl,  
Tender and slight;  
The cock’s loud crow,  
And so does yours;  
Glad-sounding voice,  
Infant murmurs;  
Merrily, merrily, to greet the coming year.

source_text:
Little boy,
Full of joy;
Little girl,
Sweet and small;
Cock does crow,
So do you;
Merry voice,
Infant noise;
Merrily, merrily to welcome in the year.

text:
They say defeat sharpens victory;
the reefs of ancient Gethsemane
make dear the shore beyond.
It is hunger that gives banquets form;
it is thirst that brings wine to life, --
faith falters to understand.

source_text:
Defeat whets victory, they say;
The reefs in old Gethsemane
Endear the shore beyond.
'T is beggars banquets best define;
'T is thirsting vitalizes wine, --
Faith faints to understand.

In all of them the poet looks upon life as it is, and the eternal
principle of beauty, in the first three seeing them in sharp contrast;
in the last reconciling them, and leaving us content.

text:
“If we bind our will beneath another’s law,
If we still fear the vile creed trampled here,
If we no longer love our kind as one!”—
She paused, then pointed upward—there they were,
Three forms around her ivory throne revealed;
One was a Giant, like a child asleep
Upon a broken rock, whose grasp had sealed,
As though in dream, the shards of crowns and scepters deep;
And one held watchful eyes, unsure to smile or weep;

source_text:
‘If our own will as others’ law we bind,
If the foul worship trampled here we fear;
If as ourselves we cease to love our kind!’—
She paused, and pointed upwards—sculptured there
Three shapes around her ivory throne appear;
One was a Giant, like a child asleep
On a loose rock, whose grasp crushed, as it were
In dream, sceptres and crowns; and one did keep
Its watchful eyes in doubt whether to smile or weep;

text:
Where are the songs that Spring once sang? Ah, where can they be?
Forget them not; your own sweet music lives to thee,--
While cloud-bars blossom in the softly fading day,
And lay a rosy tint on stubble-fields away;
Then in a plaintive host the tiny gnats lament
Among the river sallows, lifted and bent
As the light breeze breathes, or fades, or seems to die;
And full-grown lambs from hill-side hollows loudly cry;
The hedge-crickets make their song; and now, more light and clear,
The red-breast pipes from out the garden-croft anear;
And swallows gathering twitter in the sky.

source_text:
Where are the songs of Spring? Ay, where are they?
Think not of them, thou hast thy music too,--
While barred clouds bloom the soft-dying day,
And touch the stubble-plains with rosy hue;
Then in a wailful choir the small gnats mourn
Among the river sallows, borne aloft
Or sinking as the light wind lives or dies;
And full-grown lambs loud bleat from hilly bourn;
Hedge-crickets sing; and now with treble soft
The red-breast whistles from a garden-croft;
And gathering swallows twitter in the skies.

text:
Down, down, proud gorge—though it be choked;
your bearded throat, your lifted brow, dragged to the gutter;
bow your hard neck low to gifts of charity.

source_text:
Down, down, proud gorge!--though choking thee;
Thy bearded throat and high-borne forehead to the gutter;
Crouch low thy neck to eleemosynary gifts.

text:
The words of true poems give you more than poems:  
they give you the making of poems, religions, politics, war,  
peace, conduct, histories, essays, daily life, and everything else;  
they keep the balance among ranks, colors, races, creeds, and the sexes;  
they do not go after beauty—they are what beauty goes after,  
and wherever you hold them close, beauty follows, with longing, eager, love-struck.

I sing of faith, and of readiness;
for Life and Nature are not vast in what they are only now,
but greater still in what is still to come,
and from that equation I sing for you.

Tell him it wasn’t some practiced writer,
you guessed it from the way the line strained;
you could hear the bodice pulling at you,
as though it had only a child’s small strength;
you nearly took pity on it, you, it worked so hard.
Tell him—No, you may argue there,
for it would break his heart to learn it,
and then you and I would be even quieter.

The sun now wakes,
And brightens all the skies;
The merry bells ring out
To greet the spring’s surprise;
The skylark and the thrush,
The birds among the brush,
Sing louder all around
To meet the bells’ glad sound;
While all our games are seen
On the echoing green.

source_text:
The sun does arise,
And make happy the skies;
The merry bells ring
To welcome the Spring;
The skylark and thrush,
The birds of the bush,
Sing louder around
To the bells’ cheerful sound;
While our sports shall be seen
On the echoing green.

With every morn their love grew tenderer,
With every eve deeper and tenderer still;
He might not in house, field, or garden stir,
But her full shape would all his seeing fill;
And his continual voice was pleasanter
To her, than noise of trees or hidden rill;
Her lute-string gave an echo of his name,
She spoilt her half-done broidery with the same.

text:
* * * Crochallan came,  
The old cocked hat, the brown surtout—the same;  
His grizzled beard was bristling, hard and white—  
Four long nights and days had passed since shaving-night;  
His uncombed, hoary locks, wild-staring, thatched  
A head whose deep, clear thinking none could match;  
Yet, though his sharp wit stung with rugged power,  
His heart was gentle, kindly, sweet of flower.

source_text:
* * * Crochallan came,
The old cock’d hat, the brown surtout—the same;
His grisly beard just bristling in its might—
’Twas four long nights and days from shaving-night;
His uncomb’d, hoary locks, wild-staring, thatch’d
A head, for thought profound and clear, unmatch’d;
Yet, tho’ his caustic wit was biting-rude,
His heart was warm, benevolent and good.

text:
What flock like Russell told its tale;  
His voice was heard o’er moor and dale,  
He knew the Lord’s own sheep, each tail,  
Across the height;  
And saw whether they were sick or hale,  
At first clear sight.

source_text:
What herd like Russell tell’d his tale;
His voice was heard thro’ muir and dale,
He kenn’d the Lord’s sheep, ilka tail,
Owre a’ the height;
An’ saw gin they were sick or hale,
At the first sight.

text:
Thus ye dwell on high, and then  
On the earth return again;  
And the souls ye leave behind you  
Here instruct us how to find you,  
Where your other souls are joying,  
Never sleeping, never cloying.  
Here, your earth-born souls still speak  
Unto mortals of their little week;  
Of their sorrows and delights;  
Of their passions and their spites;  
Of their glory and their shame;  
What doth strengthen, what may maim.  
Thus ye guide us, day by day,  
Wisdom, though so far away.

source_text:
Thus ye live on high, and then
On the earth ye live again;
And the souls ye left behind you
Teach us, here, the way to find you,
Where your other souls are joying,
Never slumber'd, never cloying.
Here, your earth-born souls still speak
To mortals, of their little week;
Of their sorrows and delights;
Of their passions and their spites;
Of their glory and their shame;
What doth strengthen and what maim.
Thus ye teach us, every day,
Wisdom, though fled far away.

text:
He knew whose tender hand was at the latch,
Before the door had yielded her to sight;
And from her chamber-window he would catch
Her beauty, farther than the hawk’s keen flight;
And steadfast as her vespers would he watch,
For still her face was turned toward the same light;
And, faint with longing, wear away the night,
To hear her morning footfall on the stair.

source_text:
He knew whose gentle hand was at the latch,
Before the door had given her to his eyes;
And from her chamber-window he would catch
Her beauty farther than the falcon spies;
And constant as her vespers would he watch,
Because her face was turn'd to the same skies;
And with sick longing all the night outwear,
To hear her morning-step upon the stair.
